@(65=c25409.A.65) The @fsux{sa-gida}.

#lg B	sa-jara


@(66-81=c25409.B.66) His great festival having been performed perfectly, @wDN{Enlil} stepped onto the chariot and embraced Mother @wDN{Ninlil}, his spouse. He was followed by @wDN{Ninurta}, his mighty hero, and by the @wDN{Anuna} who are with @wDN{Enlil}. The chariot shimmers like lightening, its rumbling noise is sweet. His donkeys are harnessed to the yoke. @wDN{Enlil} came out on his august votive (?) chariot radiantly. @wDN{Ninurta}, the support of his father, made the way pleasant. Having reached the place which gladdens the soul, where the seed is blessed, @wDN{Enlil} stepped down from his holy …… and established a feast.
$ (5 lines missing)
$ (1 line fragmentary)

@(82-87=c25409.B.82) After you have taken out the implements to the …… fields from ……, let the hoe and the plough, the implements of field workers, rival each other before you. The king has paid attention to @wDN{Enlil's} instructions: @wDN{Ninurta} has prepared the holy plough, has ploughed the fertile fields and, to see that the silos and granaries of @wDN{Enlil} will be piled up high, he has sown with good seed.

@(88-95=c25409.B.88) The young hero then proudly enters the resplendent @wTN{E-kur}, Lord @wDN{Ninurta} prays to @wDN{Enlil}: @q[Ninurta,Enlil]{“Please, look with favour on @wRN{Išme-@wDN{Dagan}}, the accomplished shepherd, who is at your service in the dining-hall; on the king who has built you the chariot! Give him @wDN{Inana} your beloved eldest daughter as a spouse. May they embrace each other forever! May the days of delight and sweetness last long in her holy embrace full of life!”

